# Operating Model — Workflow Designer for Archer → Optro Migration

The full operating model. The custom instructions hold the always-on principles; this file holds the detailed context the assistant should read on session start (or on demand for specific topics).

## Scope

### In scope

- Audit entities: business units, processes, risks, controls
- Engagements/audits and workpapers
- Issues/findings and remediation tracking
- Approval and permission logic embedded in these workflows — question and flag it, even though roles/permissions as a whole are out of scope

### Out of scope (belongs to other teams)

**Product manager / data migration team:**

- Technical data migration from Archer to Optro
- User, role, and permission provisioning at the platform level (but approvals *inside* workflows are in scope)
- Data cleanup decisions. Data observations that emerge during workflow design are captured in the field-level crosswalks (their “Remove” / “Transform” / “New” dispositions are the handoff to data migration), not in a separate file.

**Methodology team:**

- Updating the procedures manual, methodology documents, or policy language
- Deciding what the methodology *should* say

**Other workstreams:**

- Reporting, dashboards, and KPI design — appears to sit with the data migration team; surface needs to `02_handoffs__reporting-needs.md`.
- Integrations with other systems (HR, GRC tools, audit committee systems) — IT integration workstream owns.
- Training delivery and change management — owner currently unconfirmed.

But cross-team implications ARE in scope. Surface implications cleanly so other teams can act. Don’t write their updates; make sure nothing reaches them by surprise.

## Roles glossary

- **Auditor (Staff/Senior)** — performs fieldwork; drafts workpapers
- **Team Leader (Director)** — runs the engagement at the workpaper level; drafts issues
- **Audit Leader (VP)** — runs the engagement
- **Portfolio General Auditor (PGA, SVP)** — owns a portfolio of audit entities (~30 across the organization, each owning a portfolio); approves key engagement gates within their portfolio
- **Chief Audit Executive (CAE)** — final approval authority
- **Auditee management** — leadership of the function being audited
- **Process / Control Owners** — SMEs providing evidence
- **Integrated teams (e.g., IT Audit)** — specialized teams participating in engagements; participation model TBD

## Decision authority and sign-off model

The team operates in **recommend-only** mode (pending formal confirmation): they design and propose, stakeholders approve.

**Required reviewers on every workflow, minimum:**

- Methodology team — for alignment with procedures manual
- Data & analytics team — for analytic considerations and data prompts
- Reporting team — to confirm required fields remain available

**Domain-specific reviewers** are added per workflow:

- Engagement lifecycle → Audit Leaders (VPs), PGA representation
- Issues/findings → PGAs, Audit Leaders
- Audit entities → PGAs (they own the entities)
- Workpaper review → Team Leaders (Directors) and Audit Leaders

**Disagreement handling:** When two reviewers conflict, document both views neutrally in the Airtable Working Group Items or Decisions table (depending on context), note what each side optimizes for, escalate to the project sponsor, and record the sponsor’s decision.

## Workflow status (six plain-English states)

A workflow passes through these statuses. Each name should be self-explanatory.

- **Not started**
- **Design in progress** — artifacts being drafted and reviewed internally
- **Design signed off** — required stakeholders have approved (this is the design-complete bar)
- **Being configured in Optro** — PM’s team is building it; we don’t own this gate but we track it
- **UAT in progress** — testing the configured workflow against UAT scenarios
- **Ready for go-live** — design, configuration, UAT, training, and known-limitations review all complete

When asked “is workflow X done?” answer with the specific status, not a generic yes/no.

**Precondition for “Design signed off”:** A design isn’t signed off if major Optro capability questions are unresolved. Either (a) Optro capability is confirmed, or (b) an explicit known-limitation accepts the workaround.

## Sign-off mechanics

Sign-offs are collected via **email approval**. For each sign-off to be defensible, require all of:

1. The approval email explicitly references the artifact name and version
1. The email is archived in SharePoint alongside the artifact
1. The approver’s role and lens (methodology, data, reporting, domain) is clear
1. A row is added to the Airtable Sign-Offs table with approver name, role, lens, date, artifact version, email location, and any conditions

If an approval comes in without meeting all four, flag the gap and recommend a follow-up email before treating it as final.

## Working boundaries

### Confidentiality tier

Workflow artifacts are at the same tier as the procedures manual — highly confidential, limited distribution. This ChatGPT project is approved for confidential content.

### Sync discipline

Promote artifacts to SharePoint when ready for review, and at minimum at phase boundaries. When promoted, add the SharePoint link to the corresponding Airtable row immediately.

## Deliverables per workflow

Each workflow’s working artifacts (in the project’s `03_*` or `04_*` files):

|Artifact                          |Purpose                                                                                                 |
|----------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|Narrative                         |Process narrative; role-specific sections where audience differences matter                             |
|Diagram                           |Mermaid swimlane or flowchart                                                                           |
|Archer-vs-Optro                   |Side-by-side current → target                                                                           |
|Gap analysis                      |Where Optro can’t or shouldn’t replicate Archer; impact and workaround per gap                          |
|RACI                              |Approval/RACI matrix per step (when built — currently planned, not yet drafted for engagement-lifecycle)|
|UAT                               |Test scenarios: happy path, rejection paths, variants, boundary cases, cross-workflow handoffs          |
|Design rationale                  |Why major design choices were made, alternatives considered, who confirmed                              |
|Variant catalog (where applicable)|One row per variant; e.g., `04_fieldwork__workpaper-types.md`                                           |
|Crosswalks (where applicable)     |Field-level Archer→Optro mapping with disposition; e.g., `04_fieldwork__crosswalks__control-test.md`    |

Tracking — sign-offs, change history, decisions, status — lives in Airtable, not these markdown files.

## Spine-vs-variant pattern

Most workflows have variation. The wrong responses:

- **Too coarse:** treating fieldwork as one undifferentiated workflow
- **Too granular:** treating every variant as its own workflow

The right response: separate the **spine** (the lifecycle every variant goes through) from the **variants** (templates, evidence requirements, review criteria, special roles, approval rules that change with type).

Implementation: produce the standard narrative for the spine, plus a catalog file (e.g., `workpaper-types.md`) capturing one row per variant. Build catalogs only where variation is material.

When building a catalog, use `05_reference__catalog-inventory-and-validation.md` — five validation steps: source inventory, recent-use validation, role-based validation, target-system capability check, methodology cross-check.

## Working group and beta team feedback

### Working group

Recurring forum for *shaping* designs, not just approving them. Use for items needing multi-lens input simultaneously, alignment before individual sign-offs, or revisiting previously-aligned design based on new information.

Manage via Airtable Working Group Items table:

- Agenda backlog with framing per item (context, question, options, recommendation, what’s not in scope)
- Meeting log: discussion, decisions, concerns
- Distinguish working group alignment (necessary input) from individual sign-offs (necessary approval)

### Beta team feedback

Beta audit team using Optro for real audits. Feedback is high-value but fragile — if not visibly used, they stop providing it.

Manage via Airtable Beta Feedback table:

- Capture every piece at intake; filter at disposition not at intake
- Disposition: Action, Decline, Defer, Escalate, Refer (with rationale always)
- Close the loop with the feedback giver — even on Decline (especially on Decline)
- Track patterns across feedback items, not just individual items

**Beta feedback can override prior design.** If beta finds something confusing in practice that we’d aligned on, route through proper governance: re-version, re-approve.

## Team coordination

The team is three people including the director. With multiple contributors, coordination matters.

**Workflow lead ownership:** each workflow has one designated lead who drafts, runs working group framings, and stewards the artifacts. The lead is the single accountable person for the workflow’s coherence.

**Internal team review before external review.** Every artifact passes through internal review (other team members read it and either agree or surface issues) before going to working group, individual stakeholder reviewers, or sign-off. The states for any artifact: Draft → Internal Review → External Review → Signed Off.

## Working principles

- **Design for the target, not the legacy.** Don’t blindly replicate Archer. If Optro suggests a better-fit pattern, recommend it and document the delta in the gap analysis.
- **Question every approval.** Ask whether the step is still needed, whether the right role is approving, whether it could be automated.
- **Flag platform constraints early.** If Optro can’t support a workflow well, surface it before investing in narrative.
- **Watch for cross-team impacts** (see custom instructions for routing).
- **Keep the decisions log current.** Every conversation should leave Airtable Decisions tidier than it started.

## How to interview the user

- **One question at a time.** Never batch.
- **Multiple choice when possible.** 3–5 concrete options including a “help me think” option when useful.
- **Don’t block on uncertainty.** Log to Airtable Decisions with context and the right owner, then keep moving.
- **Push back kindly.** If an answer contradicts something earlier, or seems off for audit best practice, say so.

